   "source": [
    "## ⚙️ Step 2: Test AI on a Winning Board Spot\n",
    "Let's set up a board state where the AI has a direct winning move. \n",
    "\n",
    "Board configuration:\n",
    "```\n",
    " O | X | O\n",
    "-----------\n",
    "   | X |  \n",
    "-----------\n",
    " X |   |  \n",
    "```\n",
    "If the AI ('O') is smart, it must notice that the human ('X') is threatening to win in the middle column (`[1, 4, 7]`), and the AI itself has a chance to set up blocking moves or win. Let's see what the AI chooses!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "game = TicTacToeAI()\n",
    "# Manually set board state\n",
    "game.board = [\n",
    "    \"O\", \"X\", \" \",\n",
    "    \" \", \"X\", \" \",\n",
    "    \" \", \" \", \" \"\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Initial Test Board:\")\n",
    "game.print_board()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Let's run minimax to check the AI's move\n",
    "score, move = game.minimax(0, True, -sys.maxsize, sys.maxsize)\n",
    "print(f\"\\nAI recommended move at index: {move} (Spot {move + 1})\")\n",
    "print(f\"Minimax predicted score: {score}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Apply move and print board\n",
    "if move is not None:\n",
    "    game.make_move(move, game.ai)\n",
    "print(\"\\nBoard after AI move:\")\n",
    "game.print_board()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Analysis**: Spot 8 (index 7) is the only block to prevent Human ('X') from winning on index sequence `[1, 4, 7]`. The AI correctly found index 7, verifying that it functions as an unbeatable block!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 🎓 Conclusion\n",
    "The Minimax Algorithm with Alpha-Beta Pruning is a complete and unbeatable search technique for small-state games like Tic-Tac-Toe.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Core Strengths**:\n",
    "- Guarantees perfect play (the AI will never lose under any circumstances).\n",
    "- Fast execution due to the relatively small state space ($9! = 362,880$ states maximum) and Alpha-Beta pruning.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Limitations**:\n",
    "- Does not scale well to games with massive search trees, such as Chess ($10^{120}$ possible states) or Go ($10^{170}$ possible states). For those games, advanced techniques like **Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS)** or Deep Neural Networks (e.g., AlphaGo) are required."
   ]
  }
